"1190":"1190","before 1238":"před 1238","1238":"1238","about 1190":"okolo 1190","1265":"1265","1165":"1165","1230":"1230","1296":"1296","1170":"1170","Grand Duchy of Lithuania":"Lietuvos Didžioji Kunigaikštystė","Lithuania":"Litva"},"da":{"about 1190–before 1238":"omkring 1190–før 1238","1190–1238":"1190–1238","–Male":"Afdød","1190–Female":"1190–Afdød","1230–1296":"1230–1296","1165–1265":"1165–1265","1170–Female":"1170–Afdød","1190":"1190","before 1238":"før 1238","1238":"1238","about 1190":"omkring 1190","1265":"1265","1165":"1165","1230":"1230","1296":"1296","1170":"1170","Grand Duchy of Lithuania":"Lietuvos Didžioji Kunigaikštystė","Lithuania":"Litauen"},"nl":{"about 1190–before 1238":"circa 1190–vóór 1238","1190–1238":"1190–1238","–Male":"Overleden","1190–Female":"1190–Overleden","1230–1296":"1230–1296","1165–1265":"1165–1265","1170–Female":"1170–Overleden","1190":"1190","before 1238":"vóór 1238","1238":"1238","about 1190":"circa 1190","1265":"1265","1165":"1165","1230":"1230","1296":"1296","1170":"1170","Grand Duchy of Lithuania":"Lietuvos Didžioji Kunigaikštystė","Lithuania":"Litouwen"},"en":{"about 1190–before 1238":"about 1190–before 1238","1190–1238":"1190–1238","–Male":"Deceased","1190–Female":"1190–Deceased","1230–1296":"1230–1296","1165–1265":"1165–1265","1170–Female":"1170–Deceased","1190":"1190","before 1238":"before 1238","1238":"1238","about 1190":"about 1190","1265":"1265","1165":"1165","1230":"1230","1296":"1296","1170":"1170","Grand Duchy of Lithuania":"Grand Duchy of Lithuania","Lithuania":"Lithuania","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Grand","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: nickname from Old French <i>grand</i>, <i>grant</i> ‘tall, large’, from Latin <i>grandis</i>. See also   Grant   1 and 4, compare   Degrand   and   Legrand  .","German: topographic name for someone who lived in a gravelly area, from Middle Low German <i>grand</i> ‘coarse gravel’.","German: nickname from a southern word of uncertain origin meaning ‘frustration, anger, ire’."],"variants":[{"name":"Grant","meanings":["Irish, English, and especially Scottish (of Norman origin): nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>graund</i>, <i>graunt</i> ‘tall, large’ (Old French <i>grand</i>, <i>grant</i>, from Latin <i>grandis</i>), given either to a person of remarkable size, or else in a relative way to distinguish two bearers of the same personal name, often representatives of different generations within the same family.","English: from the rare Middle English (and Old English) personal name <i>Grante</i> or <i>Grente</i>.","Irish: in Ireland this is usually the Norman Scottish name (see 1 above), but it was also adopted for Irish <b>Mag Raighne</b>, see   Graney  ."]},{"name":"Degrand","meanings":["French: patronymic, with fused preposition <i>de</i> ‘of’, from the nickname   Grand   ‘tall, large’.","American shortened form of Walloon <b>Degrandgagnage</b>, itself a variant, with fused preposition <i>de</i> ‘from’, of <b>Grandgagnage</b>, a habitational name from Grandgagnage in Wallonia (Belgium). The surname <i>Degrandgagnage</i> is not found in Belgium."]},{"name":"Grandin","meanings":["French: nickname from a diminutive of   Grand   ‘big, tall’.","Italian: from a derivative of   Grande  ."]}]},{"name":"Duke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>duk(ke)</i>, <i>duck</i>, <i>doke</i>, <i>dook</i> ‘duck’ (Old English <i>dūce</i>), either from a perceived resemblance (perhaps a waddling gait) or from association with wild fowling. Compare   Duck  ,   Drake  .","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Duk</i> or <i>Duke</i>. In northern England this is usually a pet form of <i>Marmaduke</i>. It may alternatively be a survival of one or more Old English personal names, though it is uncertain whether they were still current in the period of surname formation. Old English <i>Ducc(a)</i> is attested in placenames like Duxford (Cambridgeshire) and Duckington (Cheshire), and was perhaps interchangeable with <i>Docc</i>, attested in Doxey (Staffordshire) and Doxford (Northumberland). <i>Duke</i> could also represent Old English <i>Deowuc</i> (as in Deuxhill, Shropshire). A surname from <i>Marmaduke</i> is on record until at least 1881 and derives from the personal name <i>Marmaduke</i>, apparently an Anglo-Norman French pronunciation of Old Irish <i>Maolmaedóc</i> ‘devotee of <i>Maedóc</i>’; see   Duckett  .","Americanized form of Polish <b>Duk</b>: nickname from <i>dukać</i> ‘to stammer or falter’."],"variants":[{"name":"Dock","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Duke  .","Norwegian: habitational name from a farm named Dokk, from Old Norse <i>dǫkk</i> ‘hollow, depression’.","North German (Lower Saxony): possibly a metonymic occupational name for someone who worked in the cloth trade, from Middle Low German <i>dōk</i> ‘fabric’."]},{"name":"Doke","meanings":["English: variant of   Duke  ."]},{"name":"Duch","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Nga, Phal, Phan, Sophan, Tha, Thang, Yen.  German Kurt, Klaus.","Polish, Sorbian, and Ukrainian: nickname from <i>duch</i> ‘spirit, breath’.","Czech: from a short form of the Old Czech personal name <i>Duchoslav</i>, composed of the elements <i>duch</i> ‘spirit’ + <i>slav</i> ‘glory’ or ‘famous’."]},{"name":"Duckett","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): from the Middle English personal name <i>Duket</i>. This may sometimes have been an early Middle English pet form of an Old English <i>Ducc(a)</i>, but was more often a pet form of <i>Marmaduke</i>, especially in Yorkshire (see   Duke  ). <i>Marmaduke</i> itself is from Irish <i>Maol Maedóc</i> ‘servant of Maedóc’, <i>Maedóc</i> being the name of prominent Irish saints of the 6th and 7th centuries."]},{"name":"Duck","meanings":["English: variant of   Duke  .","Irish: adoption of the English name (see 1 above) as an equivalent of <b>Lohan</b> (an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Leocháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Leochán</i>’) by mistranslation, as if from <i>lacha</i> ‘duck’.","North German (also <b>Dück</b>) and German (<b>Dück</b>): see   Dueck  ."]},{"name":"Dukes","meanings":["English: variant of   Duke  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: possibly a metonymic occupational name for a fisherman, from <i>orfe</i>, a species of freshwater fish. Alternatively, a habitational name from Urff near Kassel, formerly Orpha."],"variants":[{"name":"Orff","meanings":["German: variant of   Orf  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Prince Dausprungus Grand Duke Of Lituania was born about 1190, in Lithuania, his father, Grand Duke Of Lithuania Ryngold, was 26 and his mother, Gertrude, was 22. He had at least 1 son with Kunigaikštytè Živinbudaité. He died before 1238."},"et":{"about 1190–before 1238":"umbes 1190–enne 1238","1190–1238":"1190–1238","–Male":"Surnud","1190–Female":"1190–Surnud","1230–1296":"1230–1296","1165–1265":"1165–1265","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1190":"1190","before 1238":"enne 1238","1238":"1238","about 1190":"umbes 1190","1265":"1265","1165":"1165","1230":"1230","1296":"1296","1170":"1170","Grand Duchy of Lithuania":"Leedu suurvürstiriik","Lithuania":"Leedu"},"fi":{"about 1190–before 1238":"noin 1190–ennen vuotta 1238","1190–1238":"1190–1238","–Male":"Kuollut","1190–Female":"1190–Kuollut","1230–1296":"1230–1296","1165–1265":"1165–1265","1170–Female":"1170–Kuollut","1190":"1190","before 1238":"ennen vuotta 1238","1238":"1238","about 1190":"noin 1190","1265":"1265","1165":"1165","1230":"1230","1296":"1296","1170":"1170","Grand Duchy of Lithuania":"Liettuan suuriruhtinaskunta","Lithuania":"Liettua"},"fr":{"about 1190–before 1238":"environ 1190–avant 1238","1190–1238":"1190–1238","–Male":"Décédé","1190–Female":"1190–Déc